    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1964-05-30T12:09:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1964-05-30T12:09:00-05:00" n="64"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d64">
                <head>64. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in the United Arab Republic</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d64fn1">Source: National Archives and Records
                        Administration, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1964–66,
                        POL <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss>-US. Top Secret;<gloss
                            target="#t_Exdis1">Exdis</gloss>. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_DRP1"
                            >Davies</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_SHM1">Symmes</persName>,
                        cleared by <persName corresp="#p_KRW2">Komer</persName>, and approved by
                            <persName corresp="#p_JJD2">Jernegan</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1964-05-30T13:09:00-04:00">May 30, 1964, 1:09 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5592. Ref <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 5567.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d64fn2">
                        <ref target="#d62">Document 62</ref>.</note> We particularly want you to
                    emphasize mischievous role of <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> missile
                    program in pushing arms rivalry to new and dangerous levels, as covered in
                    previous guidelines. We recognize of course thin line between insuring <persName
                        corresp="#p_NGA1">Nasser</persName> understands and appreciates nature of
                    this escalation and on other hand giving him impression Israel about to go
                    nuclear with our understanding and tacit support. We therefore leave to you best
                    means of convincing <persName corresp="#p_NGA1">Nasser</persName> this is game
                    he cannot win because of Israel’s technological development and access to
                    outside financial sources.</p>
                <p>Moreover, we think it important he be made to realize, in way he will not resent,
                    fact that he must shoulder large share responsibility for arms race in general.
                    His periodic opening of “icebox” door (cite cases) has let out blasts of cold
                    air that put great psychological pressure on Israelis to obtain deterrent. We
                    are not trying to justify Israeli actions to him; we are merely explaining them
                    and his responsibility.</p>
                <p>Essential facts are: <list>
                        <label>(1)</label>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> was first to opt for surface to
                            surface missile force.</item>
                        <label>(2)</label>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> is continuing to develop <gloss
                                target="#t_SSM1">SSM</gloss>s.</item>
                        <label>(3)</label>
                        <item>Reports are that Israel in response is also acquiring <gloss
                                target="#t_SSM1">SSM</gloss>s.</item>
                        <label>(4)</label>
                        <item>Once possessed of <gloss target="#t_SSM1">SSM</gloss>s and confronted
                            with a growing <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> missile force, Israel
                            might well seek to develop more lethal warheads to provide deterrence
                            against implacable Arab hostility it senses from Arab public
                            statements.</item>
                        <pb facs="0184" n="152" xml:id="pg_152"/>
                        <label>(5)</label>
                        <item>We believe Israel can be persuaded not to proceed further with <gloss
                                target="#t_SSM1">SSM</gloss> development if <gloss target="#t_UAR1"
                                >UAR</gloss> willing to demonstrate restraint.</item>
                        <label>(6)</label>
                        <item>Otherwise, we fear race will inexorably escalate.</item>
                        <label>(7)</label>
                        <item>But no good purpose served by such escalation. Situation is obviously
                            self-defeating for both sides. Not only does it make for greater danger
                            of war, it also diverts resources badly needed in development of more
                            prosperous Arab nation. Moreover, US determined forestall aggression by
                            either side, and has capability do so. So we wonder why either side
                            should engage in wasteful expensive programs, which will not achieve any
                            decisive military result.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">
                            <persName corresp="#p_BGW1">Ball</persName>
                        </hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
